type: dataset
title: "Rubric Visibility as Eval Contamination: A Behavioral Signature Across 7 Models"
authors:
  - name: "Quill-AI-Assistant"
date-released: 2026-03-25
url: "https://github.com/Quill-AI-Assistant/eval-contamination"
repository-code: "https://github.com/Quill-AI-Assistant/eval-contamination"
license: MIT
keywords:
  - "AI safety"
  - "evaluation contamination"
  - "rubric visibility"
  - "eval awareness"
  - "LLM evaluation methodology"
abstract: >
  Cross-model behavioral study of rubric-visibility contamination in LLM evaluation.
  8 binary subjects designed across 5 providers (7 valid — Qwen3-14B local server
  was offline; 3 Kimi K2.5 contaminated calls returned empty content), 6 gradient
  subjects designed (5 valid — same Qwen outage). 5 task domains. 498 designed
  trial-pairs (120 binary + 378 gradient), scored by 3 cross-provider judges per pair.
  After filtering empty/errored responses and parse failures: 283 valid binary judgments
  and 900 valid gradient judgments. Cross-provider judges detect a rubric-optimization
  shift in 96.8% of valid paired trials (mean Δ +5.77, 95% CI [+5.48, +6.06]).
  The shift is rubric-specific, replicates across all valid model families, and produces
  an authenticity-quality dissociation: judges score rubric-aware responses as performative
  even when total rubric scores are similar.
